 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'kingthorin', 'comment_id': 738918683.0, 'datetime': '2020-12-04 17:40:17+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': "Maybe it's too advanced for this content but I'll mention it anyway: This is the chained one-liner I use for updating all my repos. Doesn't matter what the default branch is because it figures that out for you (master, develop, main, whatever):
```bash
DEFAULT=$(git symbolic-ref --short HEAD) && git fetch -vp origin && git fetch -vp upstream && git merge upstream/$DEFAULT && git push
```

1. It assumes you're in the repo directory and have the default branch checked out.
1. Find the default branch name.
1. Fetch origin verbosely and prune branches that have been removed.
1. Fetch upstream verbosely and prune branches that have been removed.
1. Merge upstream into local.
1. Push back to origin.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
